{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631454"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17376"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17376"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70212"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10066"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55676"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5487"},{"type":"tags","id":"7825"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23567"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70212"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes publication bias in medical research?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Studies from academic institutions are more likely to be published","Studies with industry funding are more likely to be published","Studies with better methodology are more likely to be published","Studies with larger sample sizes are more likely to be published","Studies with positive results are more likely to be published"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudies with positive results being more likely to be published\u003C/strong\u003E represents publication bias. This systematic error in the published literature occurs because studies showing statistically significant or favourable results are more likely to be submitted and accepted for publication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudies with larger sample sizes being more likely to be published\u003C/strong\u003E - While larger studies may be of higher quality, sample size alone does not determine publication likelihood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudies from academic institutions being more likely to be published\u003C/strong\u003E - The institutional affiliation is not a major determinant of publication bias\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudies with better methodology being more likely to be published\u003C/strong\u003E - While methodological quality is important, it is not the primary factor in publication bias\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStudies with industry funding being more likely to be published\u003C/strong\u003E - Funding source alone does not determine publication likelihood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPublication bias can lead to overestimation of treatment effects in systematic reviews and meta-analyses, as negative results may remain unpublished. This highlights the importance of trial registration and publishing all results regardless of outcome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Publication bias occurs when studies with positive or significant results are more likely to be published than those with negative or non-significant results.","Publication bias can lead to overestimation of 